The punctuation sign at the end of l42 is a double vertical. It may have been meant to prevent the addition of further characters, but I can't see why some of the characters that ended up on the next page weren't inscribed here. In any case, the sign is probably a space filler. 
--><!-- 
In the clause set out in l41-43, Mirashi corrects to a-brahma° and a-kurvvatām. In this he basically follows Fleet. I'm not sure, but this doesn't seem quite convincing, and it's hard to take the compound ending with prabhr̥tīnāṁ as referring to the donees (Mirashi translates,"not found guilty of the murder of a Brāhmaṇa" and "do not wage war"). Instead, I'd leave the text as it is (except restoring an anusvāra at the end of saṁgrāmaṁ) and translate, "It (the charter) shall be valid as long as the sun and moon endure, provided that they (the donees) commit no treason against the (anytime current) kings' kingdom consisting of seven components, that they persecute (saṁgrāmaṁ kurvatām) brahman killers, thieves, adulterers and committers of treason and so on, and that they do not harm other villages." *OK, I'm vindicated. This is actually how Sircar reads and interprets this passage (#Sircar_1965:448n1), "And this condition of the charter should be maintained by the Brāhmaṇas and by [future] lords; namely [that the enjoyment of this grant is to belong to the Brāhmaṇas] for so long as the moon and the sun endure, provided that they commit no treason against the kingdom, consisting of 7 constituent parts, of [sucessive] kings; that they are always on hostile terms with slayers of Brāhmaṇas, thieves, adulterers, traitors to the king, etc.; and that they do no wrong to other villages. But, if they act otherwise or assent [to such acts], the king will commit no theft in taking the land away." #Vajpeyi_1985 argues something similar (acknowledged by #Shrimali_1987:40-41). 
--><!-- 
In l44 Fleet simply reads kurvvataḥ, while Mirashi reads kurvvantaḥ, emending to -taḥ. I don't think the reading is nt (the box head seems to have a loop, which is probably what Mirashi read as n). There is, however, a dot that looks like anusvāra above rvva. I believe it is more likely to be the top of the superscript r, with the connecting line invisible in the rubbing. 
--></p>
